an","route_type":"explicit_quran_reference","action_type":"explain","canonical_refs":["quran:112:1-4"],"query_normalized":"surah al-ikhlas","surah_no":112,"ayah_start":1,"ayah_end":4,"span_label":"Quran 112:1-4"},"answer_seed":{"lead_text":"Quran 112:1-4 says: Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺 Retrieved commentary from Tafsir Ibn Kathir, Ma'arif al-Qur'an, and Tafheem al-Quran is attached below.","summary_style":"source_grounded","must_preserve_boundaries":true,"base_quote":{"domain":"quran","canonical_ref":"quran:112:1-4","text":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺"}},"source_bundles":[{"domain":"quran","source_id":"quran:tanzil-simple","display_name":"Quran 112:1-4","role":"quran_source","scope_ref":"quran:112:1-4","text":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺","full_text":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺","focused_extract":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺","short_excerpt":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺","arabic_text":"脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脵聥脴搂 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦","translation_text":"Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique; Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need; He neither begot any nor was He begotten, and none is comparable to Him.芒聙聺","citations":["quran:112:1-4"]},{"domain":"tafsir","source_id":"tafsir:ibn-kathir-en","display_name":"Tafsir Ibn Kathir (English)","role":"comparative_commentary","scope_ref":"tafsir:ibn-kathir-en:84552","full_text":"Which was revealed in Makkah  The Reason for the Revelation of this Surah and its Virtues  Imam Ahmad recorded from Ubayy bin Ka`b that the idolators said to the Prophet , \"O Muhammad! Tell us the lineage of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed\n\n脴篓脵聬脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聟脵聬\n\nIn the name of Allah, the Beneficent, the Merciful\n\nSimilar was recorded by At-Tirmidhi and Ibn Jarir and they added in their narration that he said,\n\n脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫\n\n(As-Samad) is One Who does not give birth, nor was He born, because there is nothing that is born except that it will die, and there is nothing that dies except that it leaves behind inheritance, and indeed Allah does not die and He does not leave behind any inheritance.\n\n脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聥 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(And there is none comparable to Him.) This means that there is none similar to Him, none equal to Him and there is nothing at all like Him.\" Ibn Abi Hatim also recorded it and At-Tirmidhi mentioned it as a Mursal narration. Then At-Tirmidhi said, \"And this is the most correct.\"\n\nA Hadith on its Virtues  Al-Bukhari reported from `Amrah bint `Abdur-Rahman, who used to stay in the apartment of `A'ishah, the wife of the Prophet , that `A'ishah said, \"The Prophet sent a man as the commander of a war expedition and he used to lead his companions in prayer with recitation (of the Qur'an). And he would complete his recitation with the recitation of `Say: He is Allah, One.' So when they returned they mentioned that to the Prophet and he said,\n\n脗芦脴鲁脵聨脵聞脵聫脵聢脵聡脵聫 脵聞脵聬脴拢脵聨脵聤脵聭脵聬 脴麓脵聨脵聤脵聮脴隆脵聧 脵聤脵聨脴碌脵聮脵聠脵聨脴鹿脵聫 脴掳脵聨脵聞脵聬脵聝脵聨脴聼脗禄\n\n(Ask him why does he do that.) So they asked him and he said, `Because it is the description of Ar-Rahman and I love to recite it. So the Prophet said,\n\n脗芦脴拢脵聨脴庐脵聮脴篓脵聬脴卤脵聫脵聢脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聭脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡脵聨 脴陋脵聨脴鹿脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聨脵聣 脵聤脵聫脴颅脵聬脴篓脵聭脵聫脵聡脗禄\n\n(Inform him that Allah the Most High loves him.)\" This is how Al-Bukhari recorded this Hadith in his Book of Tawhid. Muslim and An-Nasa'i also recorded it. In his Book of Salah, Al-Bukhari recorded that Anas said, \"A man from the Ansar used to lead the people in prayer in the Masjid of Quba'. Whenever he began a Surah in the recitation of the prayer that he was leading them, he would start by reciting `Say: He is Allah, One' until he completed the entire Surah. Then he would recite another Surah along with it (after it). And used to do this in every Rak`ah. So his companions spoke to him about this saying; `Verily, you begin the prayer with this Surah. Then you think that it is not sufficient for you unless you recite another Surah as well. So you should either recite it or leave it and recite another Surah instead.' The man replied, `I will not leave it off. If you want me to continue leading you (in prayer), I will do this; and if you all do not like it, I will leave you (i.e., I will stop leading you).' They used to consider him to be of the best of them to lead them in prayer and they did not want anyone else to lead them other than him. So, when the Prophet came they informed him of this information and he said,\n\n脗芦脵聤脵聨脴搂 脵聛脵聫脵聞脵聨脴搂脵聠脵聫脴聦 脵聟脵聨脴搂 脵聤脵聨脵聟脵聮脵聠脵聨脴鹿脵聫脵聝脵聨 脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聮 脴陋脵聨脵聛脵聮脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聨 脵聟脵聨脴搂 脵聤脵聨脴拢脵聮脵聟脵聫脴卤脵聫脵聝脵聨 脴篓脵聬脵聡脵聬 脴拢脵聨脴碌脵聮脴颅脵聨脴搂脴篓脵聫脵聝脵聨脴聦 脵聢脵聨脵聟脵聨脴搂 脴颅脵聨脵聟脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聝脵聨 脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聣 脵聞脵聫脴虏脵聫脵聢脵聟 脵聡脵聨脴掳脵聬脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴鲁脵聭脵聫脵聢脴卤脵聨脴漏脵聬 脵聛脵聬脵聤 脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聬 脴卤脵聨脵聝脵聮脴鹿脵聨脴漏脵聧脴聼脗禄\n\n(O so-and-so! What prevents you from doing what your companions are commanding you to do, and what makes you adhere to the recitation of this Surah in every Rak`ah) The man said, `Verily, I love it.' The Prophet replied,\n\n脗芦脴颅脵聫脴篓脵聭脵聫脵聝脵聨 脴楼脵聬脵聤脵聭脵聨脴搂脵聡脵聨脴搂 脴拢脵聨脴炉脵聮脴庐脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聝脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴卢脵聨脵聠脵聭脵聨脴漏脗禄\n\n(Your love of it will cause you to enter Paradise.) This was recorded by Al-Bukhari, with a disconnected chain, but in a manner indicating his approval.\n\nA Hadith that mentions this Surah is equivalent to a Third of the Qur'an  Al-Bukhari recorded from Abu Sa`id that a man heard another man reciting\n\n脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(Say: \"He is Allah, One.\") and he was repeating over and over. So when morning came, the man went to the Prophet and mentioned that to him, and it was as though he was belittling it. The Prophet said,\n\n脗芦脵聢脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聭脵聨脴掳脵聬脵聤 脵聠脵聨脵聛脵聮脴鲁脵聬脵聤 脴篓脵聬脵聤脵聨脴炉脵聬脵聡脵聬 脴楼脵聬脵聠脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聨脴搂 脵聞脵聨脴陋脵聨脴鹿脵聮脴炉脵聬脵聞脵聫 脴芦脵聫脵聞脵聫脴芦脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聫脴卤脵聮脴垄脵聠脗禄\n\n(By He in Whose Hand is my soul, verily it is equivalent to a third of the Qur'an.) Abu Dawud and An-Nasa'i also recorded it. Another Hadith Al-Bukhari recorded from Abu Sa`id, may Allah be pleased with him, that the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 said to his Companions,\n\n脗芦脴拢脵聨脵聤脵聨脴鹿脵聮脴卢脵聬脴虏脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聫脵聝脵聫脵聟脵聮 脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聜脵聮脴卤脵聨脴拢脵聨 脴芦脵聫脵聞脵聫脴芦脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聫脴卤脵聮脴垄脵聠脵聬 脵聛脵聬脵聤 脵聞脵聨脵聤脵聮脵聞脵聨脴漏脵聧脗禄\n\n(Is one of you not able to recite a third of the Qur'an in a single night) This was something that was difficult for them and they said, \"Which of us is able to do that, O Messenger of Allah\" So he replied,\n\n脗芦脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聢脵聨脴搂脴颅脵聬脴炉脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 脴芦脵聫脵聞脵聫脴芦脵聫 脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聫脴卤脵聮脴垄脵聠脗禄\n\n(\"Allah is the One, As-Samad\" is a third of the Qur'an.) Al-Bukhari was alone in recording this Hadith.\n\nAnother Hadith that its Recitation necessitates Admission into Paradise  Imam Malik bin Anas recorded from `Ubayd bin Hunayn that he heard Abu Hurayrah saying, \"I went out with the Prophet and he heard a man reciting `Say: He is Allah, the One.' So the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 said,\n\n脗芦脵聢脵聨脴卢脵聨脴篓脵聨脴陋脗禄\n\n(It is obligatory.) I asked, `What is obligatory' He replied,\n\n脗芦脴搂脵聞脵聮脴卢脵聨脵聠脵聭脵聨脴漏脗禄\n\n(Paradise.)\" At-Tirmidhi and An-Nasa'i also recorded it by way of Malik, and At-Tirmidhi said, \"Hasan Sahih Gharib. We do not know of it except as a narration of Malik.\" The Hadith in which the Prophet said,\n\n脗芦脴颅脵聫脴篓脵聭脵聫脵聝脵聨 脴楼脵聬脵聤脵聭脵聨脴搂脵聡脵聨脴搂 脴拢脵聨脴炉脵聮脴庐脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聝脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴卢脵聨脵聠脵聭脵聨脴漏脗禄\n\n(Your love of it will cause you to enter Paradise.) has already been mentioned.\n\nA Hadith about repeating this Surah  `Abdullah bin Imam Ahmad recorded from Mu`adh bin `Abdullah bin Khubayb, who reported that his father said, \"We became thirsty and it had become dark while we were waiting for the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 to lead us in prayer. Then, when he came out he took me by my hand and said,\n\n脗芦脵聜脵聫脵聞脗禄\n\n(Say.) Then he was silent. Then he said again,\n\n脗芦脵聜脵聫脵聞脗禄\n\n(Say.) So I said, `What should I say' He said,\n\n脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n脵聢脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聟脵聫脴鹿脵聨脵聢脵聭脵聬脴掳脵聨脴陋脵聨脵聤脵聮脵聠脵聬 脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聠脵聨 脴陋脵聫脵聟脵聮脴鲁脵聬脵聤 脵聢脵聨脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聠脵聨 脴陋脵聫脴碌脵聮脴篓脵聬脴颅脵聫 脴芦脵聨脵聞脵聨脴搂脴芦脵聥脴搂脴聦 脴陋脵聨脵聝脵聮脵聛脵聬脵聝脵聨 脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聨 脵聤脵聨脵聢脵聮脵聟脵聧 脵聟脵聨脴卤脵聭脵聨脴陋脵聨脵聤脵聮脵聠脗禄\n\n(Say: \"He is Allah, One,\" and the two Surahs of Refuge (Al-Falaq and An-Nas) when you enter upon the evening and the morning three times (each). They will be sufficient for you two times every day.)\" This Hadith was also recorded by Abu Dawud, At-Tirmidhi and An-Nasa'i. At-Tirmidhi said, \"Hasan Sahih Gharib.\" An-Nasa'i also recorded through another chain of narrators with the wording,\n\n脗芦脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聮脵聛脵聬脵聝脵聨 脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聨 脴麓脵聨脵聤脵聮脴隆脗禄\n\n(They will suffice you against everything.)\n\nAnother Hadith about supplicating with it by Allah's Names  In his Book of Tafsir, An-Nasa'i recorded from `Abdullah bin Buraydah, who reported from his father that he entered the Masjid with the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞, and there was a man praying and supplicating saying, \"O Allah! Verily, I ask you by my testifying that there is no God worthy of worship except You. You are the One, the Self-Sufficient Sustainer of all, Who does not give birth, nor were You born, and there is none comparable to Him.\" The Prophet said,\n\n脗芦脵聢脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聭脵聨脴掳脵聬脵聤 脵聠脵聨脵聛脵聮脴鲁脵聬脵聤 脴篓脵聬脵聤脵聨脴炉脵聬脵聡脵聬 脵聞脵聨脵聜脵聨脴炉脵聮 脴鲁脵聨脴拢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴篓脵聬脴搂脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴拢脵聨脴鹿脵聮脴赂脵聨脵聟脴聦 脴搂脵聞脵聭脵聨脴掳脵聬脵聤 脴楼脵聬脴掳脵聨\n\nA Hadith about seeking a Cure by these Surahs  Al-Bukhari recorded from `A'ishah that whenever the Prophet would go to bed every night, he would put his palms together and blow into them. Then he would recite into them (his palms), `Say: He is Allah, One', `Say: I seek refuge with the Lord of Al-Falaq', and `Say: I seek refuge with the Lord of mankind.' Then he would wipe whatever he was able to of his body with them (his palms). He would begin wiping his head and face with them and the front part of his body. He would do this (wiping his body) three times. The Sunan compilers also recorded this same Hadith.\n\n脴篓脵聬脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聟脵聬\n\nIn the Name of Allah, the Most Gracious, the Most Merciful.\n\n脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦 - 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 - 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮 - 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聥 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(1. Say: \"He is Allah, One.\") (2. \"Allah As-Samad.\") (3. \"He begets not, nor was He begotten.\") (4. \"And there is none comparable to Him.\") The reason for the revelation of this Surah has already been mentioned. `Ikrimah said, \"When the Jews said, `We worship `Uzayr, the son of Allah,' and the Christians said, `We worship the Messiah (`Isa), the son of Allah,' and the Zoroastrians said, `We worship the sun and the moon,' and the idolators said, `We worship idols,' Allah revealed to His Messenger ,\n\n脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(Say: \"He is Allah, One.\") meaning, He is the One, the Singular, Who has no peer, no assistant, no rival, no equal and none comparable to Him. This word (Al-Ahad) cannot be used for anyone in affirmation except Allah the Mighty and Majestic, because He is perfect in all of His attributes and actions. Concerning His saying,\n\n脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫\n\n(Allah As-Samad.) `Ikrimah reported that Ibn `Abbas said, \"This means the One Who all of the creation depends upon for their needs and their requests.\" `Ali bin Abi Talhah reported from Ibn `Abbas, \"He is the Master Who is perfect in His sovereignty, the Most Noble Who is perfect in His nobility, the Most Magnificent Who is perfect in His magnificence, the Most Forbearing Who is perfect in His forbearance, the All-Knowing Who is perfect in His knowledge, and the Most Wise Who is perfect in His wisdom. He is the One Who is perfect in all aspects of nobility and authority. He is Allah, glory be unto Him. These attributes are not befitting anyone other than Him. He has no coequal and nothing is like Him. Glory be to Allah, the One, the Irresistible.\" Al-A`mash reported from Shaqiq, who said that Abu Wa'il said,\n\n脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫\n\n(As-Samad.) is the Master Whose control is complete.\"\n\nAllah is Above having Children and procreating  Then Allah says,\n\n脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮 - 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聥 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(He begets not, nor was He begotten. And there is none comparable to Him.) meaning, He does not have any child, parent or spouse. Mujahid said,\n\n脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聥 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦\n\n(And there is none comparable to Him.) \"This means He does not have a spouse.\" This is as Allah says,\n\n脴篓脵聨脴炉脵聬脵聤脴鹿脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴鲁脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聢脵聨脴陋脵聬 脵聢脵聨脴搂脵聞脴搂脵聭脵聦脴卤脵聮脴露脵聬 脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聭脵聨脵聣 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聫 脵聞脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聦 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脴陋脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴碌脵聨脵聙脴颅脵聬脴篓脵聨脴漏脵聦 脵聢脵聨脴庐脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聜脵聨 脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聨 脴麓脵聨脵聣脵聮脴隆脵聧\n\n(He is the Originator of the heavens and the earth. How can He have children when He has no wife He created all things.) (6:101) meaning, He owns everything and He created everything. So how can He have a peer among His creatures who can be equal to Him, or a relative who can resemble Him Glorified, Exalted and far removed is Allah from such a thing. Allah says,\n\n脵聢脵聨脵聜脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聮 脴搂脴陋脵聭脵聨脴庐脵聨脴掳脵聨 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聫 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脴搂脵聥 - 脵聞脵聨脵聜脵聨脴炉脵聮 脴卢脵聬脴娄脵聮脴陋脵聫脵聟脵聮 脴麓脵聨脵聤脵聮脴娄脴搂脵聥 脴楼脵聬脴炉脵聭脴搂脵聥 - 脴陋脵聨脵聝脵聨脴搂脴炉脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴鲁脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聢脵聨脴陋脵聫 脵聤脵聨脴陋脵聨脵聛脵聨脴路脵聭脵聨脴卤脵聮脵聠脵聨 脵聟脵聬脵聠脵聮脵聡脵聫 脵聢脵聨脴陋脵聨脵聠脴麓脵聨脵聜脵聭脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴搂脵聭脵聦脴卤脵聮脴露脵聫 脵聢脵聨脴陋脵聨脴庐脵聬脴卤脵聭脵聫 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴卢脵聬脴篓脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聫 脵聡脵聨脴炉脵聭脴搂脵聥 - 脴拢脵聨脵聠 脴炉脵聨脴鹿脵聨脵聢脵聮脴搂 脵聞脵聬脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脴搂脵聥 - 脵聢脵聨脵聟脵聨脴搂 脵聤脵聨脵聠脴篓脵聨脴潞脵聬脵聣 脵聞脵聬脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴拢脵聨脵聠 脵聤脵聨脴陋脵聭脵聨脴庐脵聬脴掳脵聨 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脴搂脵聥 - 脴楼脵聬脵聠 脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聫 脵聟脵聨脵聠 脵聛脵聬脵聣 脴搂脵聞脴鲁脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聢脵聨脴陋脵聬 脵聢脵聨脴搂脵聞脴搂脵聭脵聦脴卤脵聮脴露脵聬 脴楼脵聬脵聞脴搂脵聭脵聨 脴垄脴陋脵聬脵聣 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴鹿脵聨脴篓脵聮脴炉脴搂脵聥 - 脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聜脵聨脴炉脵聮 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聮脴碌脵聨脵聙脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脵聢脵聨脴鹿脵聨脴炉脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脴鹿脵聨脴炉脵聭脴搂脵聥 - 脵聢脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聞脵聭脵聫脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脴隆脵聨脴搂脴陋脵聬脵聤脵聡脵聬 脵聤脵聨脵聢脵聮脵聟脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聬脵聤脵聨脵聙脵聟脵聨脴漏脵聬 脵聛脵聨脴卤脵聮脴炉脴搂脵聥\n\n(And they say: Ar-Rahman has begotten a son. Indeed you have brought forth (said) a terrible evil thing. Whereby the heavens are almost torn, and the earth is split asunder, and the mountains fall in ruins, that they ascribe a son to Ar-Rahman. But it is not suitable for Ar-Rahman that He should beget a son. There is none in the heavens and the earth but comes unto Ar-Rahman as a slave. Verily, He knows each one of them, and has counted them a full counting. And all of them will come to Him alone on the Day of Resurrection.) (19:88-95) And Allah says,\n\n脵聢脵聨脵聜脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聮 脴搂脴陋脵聭脵聨脴庐脵聨脴掳脵聨 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聭脵聨脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聫 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脴搂脵聥 脴鲁脵聫脴篓脵聮脴颅脵聨脴搂脵聠脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴篓脵聨脵聞脵聮 脴鹿脵聬脴篓脵聨脴搂脴炉脵聦 脵聟脵聭脵聫脵聝脵聮脴卤脵聨脵聟脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨 - 脵聞脴搂脵聨 脵聤脵聨脴鲁脵聮脴篓脵聬脵聜脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴篓脵聬脴搂脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聨脵聢脵聮脵聞脵聬 脵聢脵聨脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脴篓脵聬脴拢脵聨脵聟脵聮脴卤脵聬脵聡脵聬 脵聤脵聨脴鹿脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聞脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨\n\n(And they say: \"Ar-Rahman has begotten a son. Glory to Him! They are but honored servants. They speak not until He has spoken, and they act on His command.) (21:26-27) Allah also says,\n\n脵聢脵聨脴卢脵聨脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聫脵聢脴搂脵聮 脴篓脵聨脵聤脵聮脵聠脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聢脵聨脴篓脵聨脵聤脵聮脵聠脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴卢脵聬脵聠脵聭脵聨脴漏脵聬 脵聠脵聨脴鲁脵聨脴篓脴搂脵聥 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聜脵聨脴炉脵聮 脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聬脵聟脵聨脴陋脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卢脵聬脵聠脵聭脵聨脴漏脵聫 脴楼脵聬脵聠脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聫脴颅脵聮脴露脵聨脴卤脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨\n\n脴鲁脵聫脴篓脵聮脴颅脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聡脵聬 脴鹿脵聨脵聟脵聭脵聨脴搂 脵聤脵聨脴碌脵聬脵聛脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨-\n\n(And they have invented a kinship between Him and the Jinn, but the Jinn know well that they have indeed to appear before Him. Glorified is Allah! (He is free) from what they attribute unto Him!) (37:158-159) In Sahih Al-Bukhari, it is recorded (that that the Prophet said),\n\n脗芦脵聞脵聨脴搂 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聨 脴拢脵聨脴碌脵聮脴篓脵聨脴卤脵聫 脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聣 脴拢脵聨脴掳脵聥脵聣 脴鲁脵聨脵聟脵聬脴鹿脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聟脵聬脵聠脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡脵聬脴聦 脵聤脵聨脴卢脵聮脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聫脵聢脵聠脵聨 脵聞脵聨脵聡脵聫 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聥脴搂脴聦 脵聢脵聨脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脵聤脵聨脴卤脵聮脴虏脵聫脵聜脵聫脵聡脵聫脵聟脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聤脵聫脴鹿脵聨脴搂脵聛脵聬脵聤脵聡脵聬脵聟脗禄\n\n(There is no one more patient with something harmful that he hears than Allah. They attribute a son to Him, while it is He Who gives them sustenance and cures them.) Al-Bukhari also recorded from Abu Hurayrah that the Prophet said,\n\n脗芦脵聜脵聨脴搂脵聞脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡脵聫 脴鹿脵聨脴虏脵聭脵聨 脵聢脵聨脴卢脵聨脵聞脵聭脵聨: 脵聝脵聨脴掳脵聭脵聨脴篓脵聨脵聠脵聬脵聤 脴搂脴篓脵聮脵聠脵聫 脴垄脴炉脵聨脵聟脵聨 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴掳脵聨脵聞脵聬脵聝脵聨脴聦 脵聢脵聨脴麓脵聨脴陋脵聨脵聟脵聨脵聠脵聬脵聤 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聨脵聡脵聫 脴掳脵聨脵聞脵聬脵聝脵聨脴聦 脵聛脵聨脴拢脵聨脵聟脵聭脵聨脴搂 脴陋脵聨脵聝脵聮脴掳脵聬脵聤脴篓脵聫脵聡脵聫 脴楼脵聬脵聤脵聭脵聨脴搂脵聤脵聨 脵聛脵聨脵聜脵聨脵聢脵聮脵聞脵聫脵聡脵聫: 脵聞脵聨脵聠脵聮 脵聤脵聫脴鹿脵聬脵聤脴炉脵聨脵聠脵聬脵聤 脵聝脵聨脵聟脵聨脴搂 脴篓脵聨脴炉脵聨脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聬脵聤脴聦 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聤脵聮脴鲁脵聨 脴拢脵聨脵聢脵聭脵聨脵聞脵聫 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴庐脵聨脵聞脵聮脵聜脵聬 脴篓脵聬脴拢脵聨脵聡脵聮脵聢脵聨脵聠脵聨 脴鹿脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聤脵聭脵聨 脵聟脵聬脵聠脵聮 脴楼脵聬脴鹿脵聨脴搂脴炉脵聨脴陋脵聬脵聡脵聬脴聦 脵聢脵聨脴拢脵聨脵聟脵聭脵聨脴搂 脴麓脵聨脴陋脵聮脵聟脵聫脵聡脵聫 脴楼脵聬脵聤脵聭脵聨脴搂脵聤脵聨 脵聛脵聨脵聜脵聨脵聢脵聮脵聞脵聫脵聡脵聫: 脴搂脴陋脵聭脵聨脴庐脵聨脴掳脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡脵聫 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聥脴搂脴聦 脵聢脵聨脴拢脵聨脵聠脵聨脴搂 脴搂脵聞脵聮脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫脴聦 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脴拢脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脴拢脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮脴聦 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聝脵聫脵聠脵聮 脵聞脵聬脵聤 脵聝脵聫脵聛脵聫脵聢脵聥脴搂 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脗禄\n\n(Allah the Mighty and Majestic says, \"The Son of Adam denies Me and he has no right to do so, and he abuses Me and he has no right to do so. In reference to his denial of Me, it is his saying: `He (Allah) will never re-create me like He created me before.' But the re-creation of him is easier than his original creation. As for his cursing Me, it is his saying: `Allah has taken a son.' But I am the One, the Self-Sufficient Master. I do not give birth, nor was I born, and there is none comparable to Me.\") This is the end of the Tafsir of Surat Al-Ikhlas, and all praise and blessings are due to Allah.","focused_extract":"Which was revealed in Makkah The Reason for the Revelation of this Surah and its Virtues Imam Ahmad recorded from Ubayy bin Ka`b that the idolators said to the Prophet , \"O Muhammad! Tell us the lineage of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed 脴篓脵聬脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聨脵聭脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聟脵聬 In the name of Allah, the Beneficent, the Merciful Similar was recorded by At-Tirmidhi and Ibn Jarir and they added in their narration that he said, 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聨脵聭脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 (As-Samad) is One Who does not give birth, nor was He born, because there is nothing that is born except that it will die, and there is nothing that dies except that","short_excerpt":"Which was revealed in Makkah The Reason for the Revelation of this Surah and its Virtues Imam Ahmad recorded from Ubayy bin Ka`b that the idolators said to the Prophet芒聙娄","units":[{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:ibn-kathir-en:84552","display_text":"Tafsir Ibn Kathir on Quran 112:1-4","excerpt":"Which was revealed in Makkah The Reason for the Revelation of this Surah and its Virtues Imam Ahmad recorded from Ubayy bin Ka`b that the idolators said to the Prophet , \"O Muhammad! Tell us the lineage of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed 脴篓脵聬脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聨脵聭脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聟脵聬 In the name of Allah, the Beneficent, the Merciful Similar was recorded by At-Tirmidhi and Ibn Jarir and they added in their narration that he said, 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聨脵聭脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 (As-Samad) is One Who does not give birth, nor was He born, because there is nothing that is born except that it will die, and there is nothing that dies except that","quran_span_ref":"112:1-4","rendering_mode":"stored_text"}],"merged_plaintext":"Which was revealed in Makkah The Reason for the Revelation of this Surah and its Virtues Imam Ahmad recorded from Ubayy bin Ka`b that the idolators said to the Prophet , \"O Muhammad! Tell us the lineage of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed 脴篓脵聬脴鲁脵聮脵聟脵聬 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聨脵聭脵聡脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聮脵聟脵聨脵聙脵聠脵聬 脴搂脵聞脴卤脵聨脵聭脴颅脵聬脵聤脵聟脵聬 In the name of Allah, the Beneficent, the Merciful Similar was recorded by At-Tirmidhi and Ibn Jarir and they added in their narration that he said, 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聨脵聭脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 (As-Samad) is One Who does not give birth, nor was He born, because there is nothing that is born except that it will die, and there is nothing that dies except that","citations":["tafsir:ibn-kathir-en:84552"]},{"domain":"tafsir","source_id":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en","display_name":"Ma'arif al-Qur'an","role":"comparative_commentary","scope_ref":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82631","full_text":"Cause of Revelation\n\nTirmidhi, Hakim and others have recorded that the pagans of Makkah asked the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 : \"0 Muhammad! Tell us about the ancestry of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed this Surah. Some narratives ascribe this inquiry to the Jews of Madinah. In view of these conflicting reports, there is a divergence of opinion as to whether this is a Makki Surah or Madani Surah. According to Sayyidna ` Abdullah Ibn Masud, Hasan Basri, ` Ata', ` Ikrimah and Jabir 脴聯 脴聦 the Surah is Makki and, according to Qatadah, Dahhak 脴卤脴颅脵聟脹聝 脴搂脵聞脵聞脹聛 脴鹿脵聞脹聦脹聛脵聟脴搂 and others, it is Madani. According to one narration of Sayyidna ` Abdullah Ibn ` Abbas 脴聯 脴聦 it is Makki and, according to another, it is Madani [ Qurtubi ].\n\nAccording to another narration, the pagans added to their question whether Allah was made of gold, silver or some other stuff, in response to which this Surah was revealed.\n\nVirtues of the Surah\n\nImam Ahmad (脴卤脴颅) has recorded a narration in his Musnad that a person came up to the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 and said, \"I love this Surah [ Al-Ikhlas ] immensely.\" The Holy Prophet 茂路潞 ' replied: \"Your love for it will cause you to enter Paradise.\" [ Ibn Kathir ].\n\nTirmidhi has recorded on the authority of Sayyidna Abu Hurairah 脴聯 that once the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 asked the people to gather and said: \"I shall recite to you a third of the Qur'an?\" When the people had congregated, he recited Surah Al-Ikhlas and said: \"This is equal to a third of the Qur'an.\" [ Muslim ].\n\nIn a lengthy Hadith, Abu Dawud, Tirmidhi and Nasa'i have recorded that the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 said: \"Anyone who recites Surah Al-Ikhlas and the mu'awwadhatain (i.e. the last two surahs of the Holy Qur'an) morning and evening, they shall be sufficient for him.\" In another narration, the wordings are: \"They will suffice him against every affliction.\" [ Ibn Kathir ]\n\nImam Ahmad (脴卤脴颅) has recorded a narration in his Musnad on the authority of Sayyidna 'Uqbah Ibn ` Amir 脴聯 that the Messenger of Allah 茂路潞 said: \"I shall show you three such Surahs that are revealed in Torah, Injil, Zabur and the Qur'an. Do not sleep at night until such time that you have recited them. They are Surah A1-Ikhlas and the mu'awwadhatain.\" Sayyidna 'Uqbah Ibn ` Amir 脴聯 says that since I have heard this, I did not miss reciting them. [ Ibn Kathir ].\n\nOneness of Allah\n\nVerse [ 112:1] 脵聜脵聫脵聞脵聮 脵聡脵聫脵聢脵聨 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聙脵聡脵聫 脴拢脵聨脴颅脵聨脴炉脵聦 Say, (The truth is: Allah is One.) The imperative qul (Say) is directly addressed to the Holy Prophet Muhammad 茂路潞 脴聦 thus indicating that he is Allah's Prophet and Messenger. This verse directs and commands him to convey Allah's message to mankind. 'Allah' is the personal name of that Necessary Being Whose non-existence is inconceivable. He comprises all the attributes of perfection and is free from, or above, or overrides all kinds of imperfections. The epithets ahad and wahid are both applied to Allah which are normally translated as 'One' but the word ahad includes an additional sense which signifies that Allah is beyond composition, plurality and resemblance, which means that He is neither composed of any elements, nor does He has any partner, nor has He any resemblance to anything. This is a response to those who asked about Allah whether He is made of gold or silver or pearls. This concise statement covers all aspects of discussion on the Divine Being and His attributes. The imperative qul [ say ] points to the messenger-ship of the Holy Prophet 茂路潞 . If analyzed properly, this brief sentence covers all the detailed discussions expounded in voluminous books of theology.\n\nVerse [ 112:2] 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聭脵聨脵聙脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聭脵聨脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 (Allah is Besought of all, needing none) The word samad bears several literal senses. Therefore, the Qur'anic exegetical scholars have assigned different meanings to this verse. Tabarani, the leading authority on Prophetic Traditions, in his kitab-us-Sunnah, has collected all the interpretations of the Divine attribute As-samad and concluded that they are all authentic, and comprehend all the attributes of our Lord that have been assigned to Him, but originally it refers to 'the chief who has no superior and to whom the people turn for the fulfillment of their desires and needs; thus all people depend on him, but he does not depend on any one.' [ Ibn Kathir ].\n\nAllah is Above having Children and Procreating\n\nVerse [ 112:3] 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮 (He neither begot anyone, nor was begotten.) This verse responds to those who had questioned about the ancestry of Allah. There is no analogy between Allah, the Creator, and His creation. While His creation comes into being through the biological process of procreation, Allah Himself has no children, nor is He the child of anyone.","focused_extract":"Cause of Revelation Tirmidhi, Hakim and others have recorded that the pagans of Makkah asked the Messenger of Allah 脴碌脵聞脵聣 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡 脴鹿脵聞脵聤脵聡 脵聢脴鲁脵聞脵聟 : \"0 Muhammad! Tell us about the ancestry of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed this Surah. Some narratives ascribe this inquiry to the Jews of Madinah. In view of these conflicting reports, there is a divergence of opinion as to whether this is a Makki Surah or Madani Surah. According to Sayyidna ` Abdullah Ibn Masud, Hasan Basri, ` Ata', ` Ikrimah and Jabir 脴聯 脴聦 the Surah is Makki and, according to Qatadah, Dahhak 脴卤脴颅脵聟脹聝 脴搂脵聞脵聞脹聛 脴鹿脵聞脹聦脹聛脵聟脴搂 and others, it is Madani.","short_excerpt":"Cause of Revelation Tirmidhi, Hakim and others have recorded that the pagans of Makkah asked the Messenger of Allah 脴碌脵聞脵聣 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡 脴鹿脵聞脵聤脵聡 脵聢脴鲁脵聞脵聟 : \"0 Muhammad! Tell us about the ancestry of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed this Surah芒聙娄","units":[{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82631","display_text":"Ma'arif al-Qur'an on Quran 112:1","excerpt":"Cause of Revelation Tirmidhi, Hakim and others have recorded that the pagans of Makkah asked the Messenger of Allah 脴碌脵聞脵聣 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡 脴鹿脵聞脵聤脵聡 脵聢脴鲁脵聞脵聟 : \"0 Muhammad! Tell us about the ancestry of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed this Surah. Some narratives ascribe this inquiry to the Jews of Madinah. In view of these conflicting reports, there is a divergence of opinion as to whether this is a Makki Surah or Madani Surah. According to Sayyidna ` Abdullah Ibn Masud, Hasan Basri, ` Ata', ` Ikrimah and Jabir 脴聯 脴聦 the Surah is Makki and, according to Qatadah, Dahhak 脴卤脴颅脵聟脹聝 脴搂脵聞脵聞脹聛 脴鹿脵聞脹聦脹聛脵聟脴搂 and others, it is Madani.","quran_span_ref":"112:1","rendering_mode":"stored_text"},{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82632","display_text":"Ma'arif al-Qur'an on Quran 112:2","excerpt":"Verse [ 112:2] 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聨脵聭脵聙脵聡脵聫 脴搂脵聞脴碌脵聨脵聭脵聟脵聨脴炉脵聫 (Allah is Besought of all, needing none) The word samad bears several literal senses. Therefore, the Qur'anic exegetical scholars have assigned different meanings to this verse. Tabarani, the leading authority on Prophetic Traditions, in his kitab-us-Sunnah, has collected all the interpretations of the Divine attribute As-samad and concluded that they are all authentic, and comprehend all the attributes of our Lord that have been assigned to Him, but originally it refers to 'the chief who has no superior and to whom the people turn for the fulfillment of their","quran_span_ref":"112:2","rendering_mode":"stored_text"},{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82633","display_text":"Ma'arif al-Qur'an on Quran 112:3","excerpt":"Allah is Above having Children and Procreating Verse [ 112:3] 脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聨脵聞脵聬脴炉脵聮 脵聢脵聨脵聞脵聨脵聟脵聮 脵聤脵聫脵聢脵聞脵聨脴炉脵聮 (He neither begot anyone, nor was begotten.) This verse responds to those who had questioned about the ancestry of Allah. There is no analogy between Allah, the Creator, and His creation. While His creation comes into being through the biological process of procreation, Allah Himself has no children, nor is He the child of anyone.","quran_span_ref":"112:3","rendering_mode":"stored_text"}],"merged_plaintext":"Cause of Revelation Tirmidhi, Hakim and others have recorded that the pagans of Makkah asked the Messenger of Allah 脴碌脵聞脵聣 脴搂脵聞脵聞脵聡 脴鹿脵聞脵聤脵聡 脵聢脴鲁脵聞脵聟 : \"0 Muhammad! Tell us about the ancestry of your Lord.\" So Allah revealed this Surah. Some narratives ascribe this inquiry to the Jews of Madinah. In view of these conflicting reports, there is a divergence of opinion as to whether this is a Makki Surah or Madani Surah. According to Sayyidna ` Abdullah Ibn Masud, Hasan Basri, ` Ata', ` Ikrimah and Jabir 脴聯 脴聦 the Surah is Makki and, according to Qatadah, Dahhak 脴卤脴颅脵聟脹聝 脴搂脵聞脵聞脹聛 脴鹿脵聞脹聦脹聛脵聟脴搂 and others, it is Madani.","citations":["tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82631","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82632","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82633"]},{"domain":"tafsir","source_id":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en","display_name":"Tafheem al-Quran","role":"comparative_commentary","scope_ref":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:1","full_text":"Verse wording:  Say: 芒聙聹He is Allah, the One and Unique;\n\nCommentary    On 芒聙聹Say:芒聙聺:  The first addressee of this command is the Prophet (peace be upon him) himself for it was he who was asked: Who is your Lord and what is He like. Again it was he who was commanded to answer the question in the following words. But after him every believer is its addressee. He too should say what the Prophet (peace be upon him) had been commanded to say.   On 芒聙聹芒聙聹He is Allah,芒聙聺:  That is, my Lord to Whom you want to be introduced is none but Allah. This is the first answer to the questions, and it means: I have not introduced a new lord who I want you to worship beside all other gods, but it is the same Being you know by the name of Allah. Allah was not an unfamiliar word for the Arabs. They had been using this very word for the Creator of the universe since the earliest times, and they did not apply this word to any of their other gods. For the other gods they used the word ilah. Then their beliefs about Allah had become fully manifest at the time Abraha invaded Makkah. At that time there existed 360 idols of gods (ilahs) in and around the Kabah, but the polytheists forsaking all of them had invoked only Allah for protection. In other words, they knew in their hearts that no ilah could help them on that critical occasion except Allah. The Kabah was also called Bait-Allah by them and not Baitilahs after their self-made gods. At many places in the Quran the polytheistic Arabian belief about Allah has been expressed, thus:   On 芒聙聹the One and Unique;芒聙聺:  In Surah Az-Zukhruf it has been said: If you ask them who created them, they will surely say, Allah. (verse 87).\n\nVerse wording:  Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need;\n\nCommentary    On 芒聙聹Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need;芒聙聺:  The word used in the original is samad of which the root is smd. A look at the derivatives in Arabic from this root will show how comprehensive and vast this word is in meaning. (Lexical discussion of the meanings of the derivatives is omitted).\n\nVerse wording:  He neither begot any nor was He begotten,\n\nCommentary    On 芒聙聹He neither begot any nor was He begotten,芒聙聺:  The polytheists in every age have adopted the concept that like men, gods also belong to a species, which has many members and they also get married, beget and are begotten. They did not even regard Allah, Lord of the universe, as supreme and above this concept of ignorance, and even proposed children for Him. Thus, the Arabian belief as stated in the Quran was that they regarded the angels as daughters of Allah. The Prophetic communities too could not remain immune from this creed of paganism. They too adopted the creed of holding one saintly person or another as son of God. Two kinds of concepts have always been mixed up in these debasing superstitions. Some people thought that those whom they regarded as Allah芒聙聶s children, were descended from him in the natural way and some others claimed that the one whom they called son of God, had been adopted by Allah Himself as a son. Although they could not dare call anyone as, God forbid, father of God, obviously human mind cannot remain immune against such a concept that God too should be regarded as a son of somebody when it is conceived that He is not free from sex and procreation and that He too, like man, is the kind of being which begets children and needs to adopt a son in case it is childless, That is why one of the questions asked of the Prophet (peace be upon him) was: What is the ancestry of Allah, and another was: From whom has He inherited the world and who will inherit it after Him.","focused_extract":"On \"Say:\": The first addressee of this command is the Prophet (peace be upon him) himself for it was he who was asked: Who is your Lord and what is He like. Again it was he who was commanded to answer the question in the following words. But after him every believer is its addressee. He too should say what the Prophet (peace be upon him) had been commanded to say. On \"芒聙聹He is Allah,\": That is, my Lord to Whom you want to be introduced is none but Allah.","short_excerpt":"On \"Say:\": The first addressee of this command is the Prophet (peace be upon him) himself for it was he who was asked: Who is your Lord and what is He like. Again it was he who was commanded to answer the question in the following words芒聙娄","units":[{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:1","display_text":"Tafheem al-Quran on Quran 112:1","excerpt":"On \"Say:\": The first addressee of this command is the Prophet (peace be upon him) himself for it was he who was asked: Who is your Lord and what is He like. Again it was he who was commanded to answer the question in the following words. But after him every believer is its addressee. He too should say what the Prophet (peace be upon him) had been commanded to say. On \"芒聙聹He is Allah,\": That is, my Lord to Whom you want to be introduced is none but Allah.","quran_span_ref":"112:1","rendering_mode":"tafheem_commentary_reconstructed"},{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:2","display_text":"Tafheem al-Quran on Quran 112:2","excerpt":"On \"Allah, Who is in need of none and of Whom all are in need;\": The word used in the original is samad of which the root is smd. A look at the derivatives in Arabic from this root will show how comprehensive and vast this word is in meaning. (Lexical discussion of the meanings of the derivatives is omitted).","quran_span_ref":"112:2","rendering_mode":"tafheem_commentary_reconstructed"},{"canonical_ref":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:3","display_text":"Tafheem al-Quran on Quran 112:3","excerpt":"On \"He neither begot any nor was He begotten,\": The polytheists in every age have adopted the concept that like men, gods also belong to a species, which has many members and they also get married, beget and are begotten. They did not even regard Allah, Lord of the universe, as supreme and above this concept of ignorance, and even proposed children for Him. Thus, the Arabian belief as stated in the Quran was that they regarded the angels as daughters of Allah. The Prophetic communities too could not remain immune from this creed of paganism.","quran_span_ref":"112:3","rendering_mode":"tafheem_commentary_reconstructed"}],"merged_plaintext":"On \"Say:\": The first addressee of this command is the Prophet (peace be upon him) himself for it was he who was asked: Who is your Lord and what is He like. Again it was he who was commanded to answer the question in the following words. But after him every believer is its addressee. He too should say what the Prophet (peace be upon him) had been commanded to say. On \"芒聙聹He is Allah,\": That is, my Lord to Whom you want to be introduced is none but Allah.","citations":["tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:1","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:2","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:3"]}],"comparative":{"enabled":true,"source_ids":["tafsir:ibn-kathir-en","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en"],"shared_points":[],"distinct_emphases":[{"source_id":"tafsir:ibn-kathir-en","points":[]},{"source_id":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en","points":[]},{"source_id":"tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en","points":[]}],"conflicts":[],"ready_for_llm_composition":true},"followup":{"followup_ready":true,"runtime_statefulness":"anchored_only","active_anchor_refs":["quran:112:1-4","tafsir:ibn-kathir-en:84552","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82631","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82632","tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en:82633","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:1","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:2","tafsir:tafheem-al-quran-en:112:3"],"source_specific_followups_supported":["What does Ibn Kathir say?","What does Ma'arif al-Qur'an say?","What does Tafheem say?","What about the first verse?"],"span_specific_followups_supported":[],"capabilities":[{"action_type":"focus_source","target_domain":"tafsir","target_source_id":"tafsir:ibn-kathir-en","target_ref":"quran:112:1-4","display_priority":10,"phrase_params":{"source_label":"Ibn Kathir"}},{"action_type":"focus_source","target_domain":"tafsir","target_source_id":"tafsir:maarif-al-quran-en","target_ref":"qura